**Operation in mathematical calculus**

This article delves into the concept of [definite integrals](/Integral) within the realm of [calculus](/Calculus). For a discussion of the [indefinite integral](/Antiderivative), which is fundamentally tied to the inverse operation, please refer to the dedicated article on [antiderivatives](/Antiderivative). If you're looking for the specific set of numbers, you might want to consult the entry on [integers](/Integer). For other uses and broader interpretations of the term, the [Integral (disambiguation)](/Integral_(disambiguation)) page awaits your perusal. Furthermore, while the phrase "Area under the curve" often evokes the geometric intuition of integration, for other uses or more specialized contexts, see [Area under the curve (disambiguation)](/Area_under_the_curve_(disambiguation)).

A [definite integral](/Integral) of a [function](/Function_(mathematics)) isn't just a number; it’s a sophisticated representation of the [signed area](/Signed_area) of the region meticulously bounded by the function’s [graph](/Graph_of_a_function) and the horizontal axis. As illustrated in the accompanying graph, consider the integral of any given function, say, $f(x)$. The total value is derived by subtracting the yellow (negative) area from the blue (positive) area. It's a precise accounting, a balance sheet of geometric contributions.

